  "prompt": "What is the square root of 40 in radical form?",
  "response": "To express the square root of 40 in its simplest radical form, follow these steps:\n\n1. **Factorize 40 into its prime factors:**\n   \n   \\[\n   40 = 8 \\times 5 = (2 \\times 2 \\times 2) \\times 5 = 2^3 \\times 5\n   \\]\n\n2. **Apply the square root to the factored form:**\n   \n   \\[\n   \\sqrt{40} = \\sqrt{2^3 \\times 5}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Simplify the square root by separating perfect squares:**\n   \n   - The term \\(2^3\\) can be written as \\(2^2 \\times 2\\).\n   - \\(2^2\\) is a perfect square.\n   \n   \\[\n   \\sqrt{40} = \\sqrt{2^2 \\times 2 \\times 5} = \\sqrt{2^2} \\times \\sqrt{2 \\times 5}\n   \\]\n\n4. **Calculate the square root of the perfect square:**\n   \n   \\[\n   \\sqrt{2^2} = 2\n   \\]\n\n5. **Combine the results:**\n   \n   \\[\n   \\sqrt{40} = 2 \\times \\sqrt{10}\n   \\]\n\n**Final Answer:**\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2\\sqrt{10}}\n\\]",
